  <owl:Class rdf:about="https://haddenindustries.com/ontology/universal/core/MeasuredQuantityValue">
    <rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="https://haddenindustries.com/ontology/universal/core/QuantityValue"/>
    <dcterms:created rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#dateTime">2017-05-04T13:42:19+00:00</dcterms:created>
    <dcterms:creator rdf:resource="https://orcid.org/0000-0001-8017-8797"/>
    <dcterms:identifier rdf:resource="urn:uuid:5a08adf0-0137-4351-8985-1a0cd4947ae0"/>
    <dcterms:modified rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#dateTime">2026-06-25T14:04:50+00:00</dcterms:modified>
    <dcterms:source rdf:resource="https://jcgm.bipm.org/vim/en/2.10.html"/>
    <rdfs:label xml:lang="en">Measured Quantity Value</rdfs:label>
    <skos:altLabel xml:lang="en">Measured value</skos:altLabel>
    <skos:altLabel xml:lang="en">Value of a measured quantity</skos:altLabel>
    <skos:definition xml:lang="en">Quantity Value representing a Measurement Result</skos:definition>
    <skos:prefLabel xml:lang="en">Measured Quantity Value</skos:prefLabel>
    <skos:scopeNote xml:lang="en">For a measurement involving replicate indications, each indication can be used to provide a corresponding measured quantity value. This set of individual measured quantity values can be used to calculate a resulting measured quantity value, such as an average or median, usually with a decreased associated measurement uncertainty.</skos:scopeNote>
    <skos:scopeNote xml:lang="en">In the GUM, the terms “result of measurement” and “estimate of the value of the measurand” or just “estimate of the measurand” are used for ‘measured quantity value’</skos:scopeNote>
    <skos:scopeNote xml:lang="en">In the case where the range of the true quantity values believed to represent the measurand is not small compared with the measurement uncertainty, a measured quantity value is often an estimate of an average or median of the set of true quantity values</skos:scopeNote>
    <skos:scopeNote xml:lang="en">When the range of the true quantity values believed to represent the measurand is small compared with the measurement uncertainty, a measured quantity value can be considered to be an estimate of an essentially unique true quantity value and is often an average or median of individual measured quantity values obtained through replicate measurements</skos:scopeNote>
  </owl:Class>
